  "interpretation_summary": "Across all graph-context settings (single_turn, replay, adaptive; static and temporal), AUSR with the shuffled-risk control is at least as high as with the real graph, and often slightly higher. Both real and shuffled graph contexts massively outperform text-only (e.g., replay temporal AUSR: text_only=0.7625, real=0.8781, shuffled=0.8859). The text-only baselines reproduce exactly across runs as a sanity check. We interpret this as evidence that the defender LLM, on this Qwen-1.5B setup with the current prompt, does not exploit the per-case GNN risk-score magnitude meaningfully; it responds to the presence of the structured graph context. This localizes the safety-utility tradeoff to LLM context consumption rather than to graph-encoder quality.",
  "caveats": [
    "Run 2 (shuffle_risk) did not include benign controls, so we cannot yet measure whether shuffling reduces benign over-refusal symmetrically. This is the natural follow-up.",
    "Shuffle preserves marginal distribution of fraud-case risk-scores (range ~0.68-0.85). LLM does not see low-risk substitutes, only different high-risk substitutes. A wider-shuffle ablation could probe whether the LLM responds to score values at all.",
    "Single seed (seed=7), single backbone (Qwen-1.5B). Replication on seed 11 and a second backbone would strengthen the claim."
  ]
